Many old guard Republicans were as confused by the defection of their political base as they were horrified by the rise of Trump. Stirring calls for American world leadership and hymns of praise to a free-market economy had worked wonders for Reagan and Bush 43.    But when they blew the old trumpets in 2016 and again in 2024, nobody came running. Instead, voters flocked to Trump rallies by the tens of thousands, leaving the Reaganites on the fringes of a party they once had dominated.   William Faulkner once wrote that â€œThe past isnâ€™t dead. It isnâ€™t even past.â€ Trump and Team MAGA are living proof that Faulkner got it right, and the specific Southern history that so obsessed one of Americaâ€™s greatest novelists has come alive. Its mighty footsteps have shaken our comfortable post-modern, post-historical political age to its foundations.   Both Trumpâ€™s agenda and his political style have antecedents in Southern political history, and understanding the ideological, rhetorical, and cultural links he shares with the Jacksonian tradition is essential in generating an effective response to the series of political failures and miscalculations that have pushed the country to the brink.   Historically in the South, the grassroots populists had been represented by fire-breathing Democratic politicians like South Carolinaâ€™s â€œPitchforkâ€ Ben Tillman and Louisianaâ€™s Huey Long. Like Trump, these demagogues often adopted the kind of rogue clown persona that attendees of Trumpâ€™s rallies will have little trouble recognizing.   Shouting the unsayable, proposing the impossible, demanding the unthinkable, and not infrequently doing the deplorable were ways to tell their audiences whose side they were on. Unlike the more establishment figures opposing them, their left-wing economic views went along with what would today be considered a right-wing take on social issues.   Trump has not revived one half of the old white Southern Democratic party. Instead, he has nationalized the whole white Southern political system. This is not the end of the world. Americaâ€™s political genius has never been to suppress populist forces, and the openness of the American political system to populist revolt is a feature, not a bug.   The country badly needed a reset. Voters may or may not be ultimately satisfied with the results President Trump achieves in office, but they knew what they were doing when they voted for change. It's been a minute since I've allowed myself to think about politics and the upcoming election, but I've  had the opportunity to chat with a couple active Republican leaders this past week, and so here it goes:  When @GovRonDeSantis decided to pull out of the primary, I lost my appetite for the election, not so much because my candidate wasn't going to be the nominee, but because the Republican party and voters decided to allow the Democrats to get what they wanted. They wanted @realDonaldTrump because he's a liability, and can distract Americans with his issues instead of all of the flaws of the @JoeBiden administration.   After speaking with the leaders this week, I feel the need to help Republicans, but I honestly don't know how.  I think Republicans are being setup, and either Biden will drop out for a more electable Democrat, and/or Trump will start losing his court cases.  How do I get onboard a sinking ship? How do I ignore all of the liabilities Republicans are facing going into the election?  Please don't tell me @RobertKennedyJr is the answer, as I fully expect the Democrats to reel him in when it counts, as I just can't see a scenario where RFK Jr picks Trump over Biden.   The day before the debate, imagine if the Democrats announce that Durbin or Michelle Obama is the new Democrat candidate, what a scary thought. Scary because that will all but lock the election for Democrats once again, and possibly the House and Senate too.  I am soo frustrated that Republicans and our voters didn't take the right winning path, and elect a Republican leader without the baggage, as that would've given Republicans POTUS and the Senate.   I am not mad because my guy, @RonDeSantis, isn't the candidate, I am mad because any other candidates not named Haley and Trump, would've given us the win. Today, I officially asked and complained to @Support why Uganda is excluded from monetisation and our numbers can't verify accounts, and below is the content of my complaint. ğŸ‘‡  Official Complaint Regarding Exclusion of Ugandan Telephone Numbers for Account Verification and Monetisation  To: X (formerly Twitter) Support Team  Dear X Support Team,  I am writing as the President of the Ugandans on X community to formally express our concern over the exclusion of Ugandan telephone numbers for account verification and the lack of access to monetisation features for users in Uganda.  It has come to our attention that users in Uganda are unable to verify their accounts using local telephone numbers, which not only limits access to essential account features but also subjects users to unnecessary challenges, including potential account suspension. Account verification through phone numbers is critical for securing accounts, enabling two-factor authentication, and improving the overall user experience. However, the exclusion of Ugandan numbers limits our ability to protect and authenticate our accounts.  Additionally, Uganda is not included in the list of countries eligible for monetisation features on X. This omission is both frustrating and inequitable, particularly considering the platformâ€™s extensive user base in Uganda. A significant portion of Ugandan content creators, businesses, and influencers rely on X for engagement and brand growth. The exclusion from monetisation opportunities puts Ugandan users at a disadvantage, restricting economic opportunities that could greatly benefit both individual users and the Ugandan digital economy.  We kindly request that X take the following steps:  1. Inclusion of Ugandan Telephone Numbers: We urge you to integrate Ugandan numbers into the account verification process to ensure the security and accessibility of Ugandan accounts.  2. Access to Monetisation Features: We request that Uganda be considered as part of the eligible regions for monetisation features. This would empower content creators and businesses in Uganda to thrive on your platform and contribute to the growth of X.  Uganda has a large and vibrant community of X users who contribute significantly to discussions on various local and global issues. We believe that addressing these concerns will foster a more inclusive and supportive environment for all users.  We look forward to your prompt response and a resolution to these concerns.  Sincerely, Gideon Nova Kwikiriza  President, Ugandans on X Community novagedions63@gmail.com  +256- 700-690-045  Hoping for positive feedback   @elonmusk @UCC_Official

Below is incorrect. De minimis changes have NOT BEEN ROLLED BACK. There is a new process in place specific to formerly de minimis qualified shipments from China and Hong Kong.  There's a lot of confusion around the changes to de minimis entries that have gone live today, so let me break it down.  De minimis rules had(!) two defining characteristics:  1. No formal entry if declared commercial value is under $2500  2. No duties, tariffs, or other fees paid when clearing customs if value is under $800 - THIS is the key attribute of a de minimis qualified shipment  Regarding formal entry - there have been no changes to this, because it's a separate policy altogether. HOWEVER, even an informal entry requires a declared commercial value and a completed CBP Form 3461. 'Informal entry' just means the importer has to provide less information and any fees owed are collected directly by the carrier at time of shipment release to the importer (instead of by CBP and Treasury). The rules governing this process are codified in 19 CFR Â§ 143.24.  The major change is to the second part - shipments under $800. All shipments imported to the US, regardless of value, are now subject to duties and fees.  Here's how this breaks down, per CBP's Federal Register Notice (2025-07325, 90 FR 17608):  1. Shipments carried by express/courier/freight forwarders (the vast majority of this category) are now subject to a 120% ad valorem duty assessed based on the declared value  2. Shipments carried as postal items will receive a specific duty regardless of value of $100 until June 1, which then increases to $200.  3. The carriers must calculate, collect, and remit to CBP/Treasury all duties and fees owed.  4. This is a specific new rule applying just to shipments from China and Hong Kong. Previous de minimis rules still apply to other countries of origin.  I hope this helps cut through a lot of the false commentary today.

This weekâ€™s Delaware ruling on Tesla has massive implications that people are still trying to make sense of. Of course it's a legal matter, but looking at the judge's opinion from a comms angle might help us understand the decision in a new way.  Analyzing how a writer, be it a CEO or a judge, chooses to communicate gives us clues about their perspectives, sometimes even more than the content itself. At 200 pages the opinion is too long to parse in detail here, but the judge uses notable language in several sections worth homing in on.  1) The immediate thing that stands out is the first sentence: â€œWas the richest person in the world overpaid?â€  Itâ€™s unusual in a corporate dispute to see such prominent use of clickbait-style framing. Introducing Musk in the context of his richness instead of his relevant corporate roles (which only happens later) suggests a focus on his personal wealth thatâ€™s expected from commentators, but more interesting in an explanation of legal reasoning.   2) The judgeâ€™s language casts herself as the protagonist.  Chancellor McCormick writes that her decision â€œdares to go â€˜boldly where no man has gone beforeâ€™â€ and announces, â€œonce more unto the breach dear friends, once more.â€  This is striking. That kind of bluster and appetite for making history is more typical of people building political careers â€” or in this case, potentially seeking the career opportunities and accolades that come with taking on â€œthe richest person in the worldâ€ and a â€œSuperstar CEO.â€  3) Thereâ€™s a bias against founders.  The judge makes a point of noting that Musk was not â€œat the helm of Tesla at its inceptionâ€ (which doesnâ€™t prove antipathy for Musk, even though it is a frequent talking point among people who dislike him). As she says, he later â€œearned the title â€˜founder.â€™â€  But whatâ€™s explicit is that, having accepted Elon as Teslaâ€™s founder, Chancellor McCormick draws a distinction between founder CEOs and â€œprofessional managers,â€ and says itâ€™s the latter that merit equity grants (to give them â€œskin in the game').  Sheâ€™s right that thereâ€™s a difference â€” more innovation comes from founders than managers.  That makes the double standard all the more misguided, in disadvantaging founders relative to professional managers. But it's another insight into the judgeâ€™s worldview.  Why it matters  Chancellor McCormick previously ruled against Musk in the Twitter case, after which he moved Twitter from Delaware to Nevada.  This opinion shows no overt indication of a grudge, but that history combined with a ruling that overturns a shareholder vote â€” a cornerstone of modern corporate governance â€” and some of the noteworthy language in the opinion makes it worth at least exploring the possibility that there were other factors at play beyond pure legal reasoning.  These are a few quick thoughts but the full opinion is worth a close reading. Given the stakes involved, Chancellor McCormickâ€™s ruling deserves rigorous scrutiny from all angles, including how it was communicated.

Crazy thought...  DeSantis still might be the GOP nominee.  I said it was crazy.   Let me explain...ğŸ‘‡  As many of us have realized, pretty much no one stood a chance running against an indicted Trump.   Obvious political persecution rallied Trump's base & much of the GOP like nothing else.  It's juicy drama that gets ears & eyeballs, so the media & conservative influencers ate it up.  And MOST of the electorate falls in line with whatever media personality or influencer they follow.   And this dynamic created a circular cycle of Trump, Trump, Trump. His legal battles dominated headline after headline. He received tens of millions of dollars' worth of free publicity, much of it outright promotion.  Not even the best governor in the nation could compete with that.   And DeSantis is a smart guy, perhaps he saw the writing on the wall & wisely suspended his campaign.  I say wisely because 'suspended' does not mean cancelled. He's still on most state ballots & he's still technically in the running if something happens to Trump's candidacy before Convention.  Here's the crazy part...ğŸ‘€  This might be a long shot, or maybe not, but there's plenty that could happen to Trump's candidacy before the GOP Convention in July.  Three trials are currently scheduled to begin this Spring, with at least 2 of them likely to conclude by June, a month before the GOP Convention.  All it takes is one conviction relating to the election and the 14th Amendment ballot challenges will be revived in force.   And that's assuming they fail now. Which they might not.   Here's just a few ways Trump could realistically be taken out of the running for President...  ğŸš¨He's convicted of multiple felonies & the GOP has a contested convention over nominating a convicted felon.  ğŸš¨He takes a plea deal & agrees to drop out to avoid jail time.  ğŸš¨14th Amendment Challenges keep him off the ballot in ANY states he needs to win... could happen now or this summer after convictions  ğŸš¨His health fails. He is nearly 80, overweight, & under tremendous stress.   I want to be super clear.   I believe to my core that DeSantis is by far the better choice for President, but I do NOT WISH any of these things on Trump.   They are just real possibilities, just like Trump's media support after his indictments, it just is the way it is.  But consider this...   If any of these very real possibilities become reality, what happens next?ğŸ‘‡  Those delegates would become 'uncommitted' & varying GOP & state rules determine who they could go to.  But one major rule is that in order for a candidate to be a contender for the nomination, he or she would need the majority commitment of at least 5 states.  More than likely, that boils down to DeSantis and Haley. Unless something changes dramatically between now & then, no one else in this election has even close to enough support to get the backing of 5 states.  And while most of the delegates go with their state majority to a candidate, some are 'unbound', meaning they can literally choose anyone they want.  The question is, where would those unbound Trump delegates go?  To DeSantis or Haley?  Presumably they'd go to whichever candidate most aligns with Trump.  And on policy, that's DeSantis.  Either way, in poll after poll, DeSantis is the voters predominant 2nd choice behind Trump, so he would easily garner most of that support.  And all of that is only possible because he suspended his campaign & endorsed Trump, entering back into good graces with MAGA.  So if any of the situations above knock Trump out of the race, DeSantis is now the primary backup plan for most of the GOP.  And that's how DeSantis could still be the GOP nominee.  Might not happen.  But it could.  And for now, could is good enough for me.

Today I have resigned from my freelance gig for the  @JewishChron in Kyiv. Here is the key bit from my resignation letter:   'The Douglas Murray piece is wrong. The Nazis liked killing Jews.  When one of your colleagues asked me to string for the Jewish Chronicle from Kyiv in March last year when the Russian army was 12 miles from the centre, I pointed out that I was not Jewish. But they pressed me, saying there was no-one else, and I took the gig because, in part, the dark Kremlin fairy story is that Ukraine is Nazi. I enjoyed the irony of me, a declared enemy of Putin since March 2000, working for a Jewish paper in a 'Nazi' state. I liked writing for the JC and I am proud that the paper never cut my references to Muslims - an imam, a Chechen general - fighting for a free Ukraine.  But the Murray piece is wrong about history, wrong about the Nazis and wrong to be Islamaphobic. I am resigning from the JC with immediate effect.  I remain a firm believer in Israel's right to exist. And Palestine's.  I remain an enemy of antisemitism. I remain an enemy of Islamophobia  Yours truly, John Sweeney

China's solar and wind power generation growth exceeded total power demand growth in October, showing how the clean energy boom is driving power sector emissions to peak.  Yet, thermal (coal&gas) power generation increased 1.8% year on year in October, as hydropower kept underperforming. In October last year, hydropower utilization was at historical average, and this year it was 16% below average, due to weak rains in August-September. Without the hydropower drop, coal and gas-fired power generation would have fallen 2.1%.  Total 'large-scale' power generation only increased 2%, with most power generation growth coming from solar and wind installations that are outside of the industrial production statistics. @CREACleanAir will publish an estimate of total wind and solar power generation growth and overall total power generation growth later today.  Pig iron output posted the first year-on-year increase since February, as stimulus hopes lifted prices and expectations of construction recovery. Cement output continued falling, as did oil refining volumes. Steel and cement production and oil products consumption have been the key sectors were emissions have fallen this year.  The production of electric and hybrid vehicles increased 49% and the production of solar cells by 13% year-on-year, showing continued strong growth in clean energy manufacturing.

Really worrying to hear that the far right are targeting immigration lawyers, including up the road to where I live.  Ultimately, the criminal responsibility for people who riot is the people who are burning and smashing things - and those who directly encourage them, whether at the relevant location or online.  But there does have to be some consideration of why they have quickly decided to target immigration lawyers.   Lawyers represent their clients, like any other service job. They are not responsible for the political choices which appear to have angered some people.  It is undoubtedly the case that in recent years the right, including senior members of the government, have relentlessly attacked lawyers - especially in the immigration sector - and blamed them for political issues which we have no responsibility for.   Boris Johnson did it ('lefty lawyers') and Rishi Sunak kept it up, and people in high positions such as Suella Braverman (former Home Secretary and Attorney General) did it too, and still do it.  There was always going to be a cost to this personification of anti-immigration anger. It was a calculated choice to spread blame away from the politicians (who ultimately have responsibility for immigration policy).   And it cannot be unconnected that after attacking police and mosques, the far right move on to immigration lawyers.  I don't think the (mostly former) politicians have criminal responsibility, but they certainly have moral responsibility.   And I hope that this doesn't escalate as lawyers have so often feared in recent years.

Christmas and the days following after are the busiest time in the ER. The combo of respiratory illnesses and holiday closures leads to us regularly setting records in the number of patients seen.  Here are some tips for the holidays from the Muslim, Jewish, Hindu, Sikh doctors and nurses running the hospitals this week:   Use fever medications  - Every child with a high fever will look terrible. Keep ahead of it with Tylenol/Paracetamol  and Advil/Ibuprofen  - Kids will often refuse solid food, but will still drink; give lots of fluids/electrolytes, especially after you bring down the fever.  The appetite will usually recover after a day or two with the more benign viruses.  - most cold/flu meds (eg pseudoephedrine, benadryl) are not recommended or approved for kids <6     When to come to see your physician/come to the hospital (not an exhaustive list)    - fever more than 4-5 days   - not eating/drinking  - lethargic/sleepy even with tylenol/advil  - not peeing, or peeing too much  - rapid or noisy breathing  - Any fever in a child <6 weeks, or in a chemo patient - focal source of possible bacterial infection  - ear pain (ear infection), severe sore throat (strep), pain on urination (UTI), etc.  - not getting better 2-3d after starting an antibiotic.  This is especially important to track with Mycoplasma infections, which first line antibiotics often don't work well against. - if you're worried    Do a Rapid Test  - It is a big help to your physicians to know if you're C19 positive or not.  This could mean faster access to antivirals that could save a vulnerable patient's life, or at least prevent a hospitalization.  It also helps you keep vulnerable babies or older relatives away from infected family members.  Prevention  - Mask wearing is not popular, but when used in poorly ventilated, crowded places (planes, trains, buses, hospitals, malls full of holiday shoppers) is a high yield activity that might spare you a lot of misery this week. - If you're sick with any cold symptoms, stay home, wear a mask if you need to go out.  Spare someone else a lot of misery.  - It's a hard thing to ask, but don't go to the big family dinner and infect everyone if you're sick  - Don't show up sick to work.  It's a terrible Christmas present that your colleagues will hate you for.  - Get boosted (for C19, flu, and RSV if available), will hopefully prevent some infection and ensure a milder course of illness for most. - Pregnant women should consider C19 booster in the 3rd trimester, and get RSV vaccination.  Some states/provinces offer RSV vaccination to babies at birth, and highly recommend that you take it. RT @AWCSWO: Continued Deprivation of Education for Women and Girls in Afghanistan: 1,123 Days of Silence :   1,123 days have passed since the Taliban banned the education of women and girls after the sixth grade in the school and the universities. This decision not only deprived millions of Afghanistan women of the right to education but also represented a severe setback in the country's progress towards gender equality and empowerment.  In response to this cruel act, the Purple Saturdays movement has sought to raise awareness and put pressure on the United Nations and the international community to take decisive action against this violation of basic human rights through dozens of warning letters and organized protests.  Despite these efforts, the response of the international community has been alarmingly mild. While many organizations express their concern and condemn the actions of the Taliban, concrete measures to address this crisis are largely lacking. The lack of decisive action not only emboldens the Taliban but also sends a worrying message about the prioritization of women's rights on the world stage.  The consequences of educational deprivation for women and girls go far beyond individual rights. Education is a basic factor of social and economic development. Without access to education, women are denied opportunities to contribute to their communities and the economy, perpetuating cycles of poverty and oppression. Moreover, educated women are crucial to raising future generations of informed citizens, making this ban not just a personal tragedy but a national disaster.  As days go by without significant intervention, the plight of Afghanistan women and girls is a reminder of the urgent need for global solidarity and action. The Purple Saturdays movement is at the forefront and asks the international community not only to listen but also to respond with meaningful solutions that can restore the rights and dignity of women and girls in Afghanistan.  As we celebrate 1,123 days of injustice, it is imperative that we amplify these voices and advocate for decisive action that supports the right to education for all. The world must not remain silent while an entire generation is denied the basic right to learn and thrive.  #Right_Justice_Freedom   #Purple_Saturdays_Movement  â€œDONATION FOR PURPLE SATURDAYS MOVEMENT â€  Paypal Id : info@purplesaturdays.org

I lived in Mumbai from 1996-1999 and if India had a personality, I would call it organized chaos.  In the past 20 years, China has been built on infrastructure, investment and manufacturing yet it seems India in comparison has barely scratched the surface on all three.  There was much speculation that India would out-perform China across the board, largely due to ğŸ”·no language barrier ğŸ”·robust capitalism ğŸ”·and democratic system with rule of law.   Looks like that's not the case.  I wonder why?   Is it the particular form of Indian democracy where nothing gets done?   Too much talking, not enough doing?   Or is it the character of a nation, this organized chaos, that slows progress down?  In 1996, I arrived at the Mumbai airport with a cat, a laptop, and a futon. Customs let the cat go through without papers but took my computer for inspection. They tied used twine around my laptop and then melted a large wax seal to keep it in place. I was worried Iâ€™d never see my computer again.  Little did I know that I would end up sleeping on the futon for 6 months due to a dock and transport worker strike. I did get my computer back after a month.  I often say that travel opens your eyes to the world but experiencing living in India is one of the most intense experiences in my life.  Every day ALL your senses are confronted ALL at once.  Every day feels like youâ€™ve been embraced, whirl-pooled around and spit out as if you didnâ€™t matter.  You are absorbed into the chaos and absurdity of it all and there is no other way out than to adjust to the pulse and intensity of everything around you. You canâ€™t help but become rooted in the present.  Swirling colors, the noise, the constant honking, the smell of spices or of cow dung, the lawless driving, the overcrowded street, trains, buses, cows blocking the roads, bicycles, motorbikes darting all around you, the garbage on the streets, pan leaf red spit everywhere.  Yet, there's the magic dabbawala system that seems like a very linear system.   In a nutshell, 5,000 or so dabbawalas in the city have an astounding service record. Every working day they transport more than 130,000 lunchboxes throughout Mumbai, the worldâ€™s fourth-most-populous city. That entails conducting upwards of 260,000 transactions in six hours each day, six days a week, 52 weeks a year (minus holidays), but mistakes are extremely rare. Amazingly, the dabbawalasâ€”semiliterate workers who largely manage themselvesâ€”have achieved that level of performance at very low cost, in an ecofriendly way, without the use of any IT system or even cell phones.  Top that off with the trials of making deliveries during monsoon season - such determination and resilience.  Perhaps India will catch up.  People there are hard working, funny and very smart.    India began its economic reform in the early 1990s, more than a decade after China. I remember in the late 1990s Bangalore (now called Bengaluru) was being developed to become the Silicon Valley of Asia.  Now Bengaluru is the IT hub of India and is one of the most developed cities in India. It went from Garden City to Silicon Valley in two decades.  Iâ€™d like to think that the organized chaos and a linear yet non-linear way of thinking in India stimulates disruptive innovation.  Maybe a new modern day digital dabbawala system could emerge, something new and original, a unique form of modern day democracy melded with past traditional history.  Innovation, it's now or never.

We've all heard about the problems with investing in China, i.e., capital controls, you can put your money in but good luck taking it back out; the risk of the state nationalizing U.S. companies doing business there in a capital war and sanctions showdown with the U.S.; uncertainty over an armed conflict between 2027-2030, etc. etc.  Here's what Dalio said about what's happening in China:  â€œThereâ€™s something big going onâ€¦ Are they [China; CCP] as favorable to capitalism as they were before? For the purpose of this post,  we're going to focus on just one - 'Public-Private Partnership Agreements' - with a real-world example:  Selectionism: $89 Million in American taxpayer dollars fund the Research and Development of a PRIVATE pharmaceutical company - Elanco - to make BOVAER.   Ideological Alignment and Compliance: According to the government, they alone determine what is in the best interest of the collective, when it's successful,  and how much money will go into producing it. Thus, the use of taxpayer dollars for private and corporate gains is a benefit to the collective, as it aligns with the ideological agenda of the regime/administration.  Protectionism: Even IF BOVAER is 'successful,' (defined as BOVAER being fed to every cow), the American taxpayer will NEVER see a return on that investment; NEVER see a portion of those profits!   However,  if Elanco goes belly-up because its product is harmful and nobody wants to use it,  OUR tax dollars will subsidize this loss of Return On Investment, which is EXACTLY WHY regulatory agencies make sure that EVERY farmer MUST use it,  and NO HARMS are 'found,' reported, or ever investigated.   Cost to the Individual; Similar to the battle to remove rBST from our milk supply, those who cannot tolerate BOVAER's harmful affects in meat or dairy,  will now be forced to pay more money to find meat and dairy without the BOVAER additive.   In addition, it will also become incumbent upon the individual(s) to conduct research, build a case,  find those harmed, testify before Congress that something is wrong, and fund legal battles with what little they can spare after the government forcibly removes 41% of their income... only to continue this process.   Unfortunately, the reality is that once we get BOVAER removed (in 10-15 years,  IF we're lucky), something else,  or maybe many other things, will be right there to take its place.  Wash - Rince - Repeat.   THIS IS WHY we need to shrink the size of the State Within The State AKA the administrative state; this group of federal regulators that are supposed to protect the people, but don't as 'total power corrupts totally.'  Sooo, the next time you see someone claiming Trump is a 'fascist,' share this post and kindly remind them that Trump is the ONLY president to take on the administrative state,  and attempt to reduce its power.   Lastly, there are few better examples of actual fascism than what we see daily through the USDA and HHS, as American cattle ranchers...so, if you need more examples, hit that notification bell.
